// ERROR: nullable enum
// WO-NullableEnumAggregate-Refuse PA-A T1 (O recon 2026-07-18): a
// payload-bearing nullable enum `E?` as a STRUCT FIELD silently overflows
// the 8-byte slot reserved for it into the next declared field. Root
// cause: `resolve_aggregate_size`'s `Nullable(Enum)` arm looked the payload
// up in `struct_map` (always a MISS for an enum name) instead of
// `enum_map`, so the co-fixpoint never grew the field past its 8B seed
// while the enum itself is 16B (disc@0 + payload@8). Before this refuse
// (guard poisoned out, measured live): `s.tail` read back `42` instead of
// `7`, exit 0 — a silent-miss, not a crash. Bare `E::V(42)` (no `~+`)
// reaches this through implicit widening, a different AST path than
// `Expr::OutcomeConstructor` (which fixture 376 already covers) — this
// fixture exercises the DECLARATION-time chokepoint (`lower_program`,
// struct-field pass), which fires regardless of how the value is built.
enum E { V(Integer), N }
struct S { e: E?, tail: Integer }
function main() -> Integer {
    let s = S { tail: 7, e: E::V(42) };
    return s.tail;
}
